<h2>8 Strategies to Get Cited by Perplexity</h2>
<p>These strategies come from analyzing which pages consistently earn Perplexity citations across competitive queries.</p>
<h3>Strategy 1: Lead With the Answer (BLUF Method)</h3>
<p>BLUF stands for Bottom Line Up Front. Place your core answer in the first 100 words of the page. Do not make readers (or AI) scroll through an introduction to find the answer.</p>
<p><strong>Bad approach:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>"Before we discuss the best CRM for small business, let us talk about what a CRM is, why you need one, and the history of customer relationship management..."</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Good approach:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>"The best CRM for small business in 2026 is HubSpot CRM (free tier) for companies under 10 employees and Salesforce Essentials ($25/user/month) for teams needing automation."</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Perplexity extracts the direct answer. If your answer is clear, concise, and in the first paragraph, your citation chances increase dramatically.</p>
<h3>Strategy 2: Structure Content for Machine Extraction</h3>
<p>AI systems parse HTML structure to find relevant sections. Make extraction easy:</p>
<ul>
<li>Use descriptive H2 and H3 headings that state the topic (not clever puns)</li>
<li>Put key claims in the first sentence of each section</li>
<li>Use tables for any comparison data</li>
<li>Use numbered lists for sequences and processes</li>
<li>Keep paragraphs under 3 sentences</li>
<li>Bold key terms and statistics</li>
</ul>
<p>Each H2 section should function as a standalone answer to a sub-question. Perplexity often cites a specific section, not your entire page.</p>
<h3>Strategy 3: Match Content Format to Query Type</h3>
<p>The LLMClicks study found that format matching is one of the strongest citation signals:</p>
