<td>Pricing table or range breakdown</td>
<td>"SEO agency pricing"</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>If the top Perplexity result for your target query uses a list format, your guide format is at a disadvantage. Check what format Perplexity currently cites for your target queries and match it.</p>
<h3>Strategy 4: Publish and Update Frequently</h3>
<p>Freshness is non-negotiable for Perplexity. Half of all Perplexity citations come from content published in the current calendar year.</p>
<p><strong>Recommended update cadence:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Statistics posts: Monthly</li>
<li>Tool comparisons: Quarterly</li>
<li>Guides and how-to content: Every 6 months</li>
<li>Evergreen definitions: Annually</li>
</ul>
<p>Add visible "Last updated: [date]" indicators to your pages. Perplexity reads these date signals. A page updated this month outperforms an identical page last updated 18 months ago. Build a <a href="/blog/content-refresh-strategy/">content refresh strategy</a> into your editorial calendar.</p>
<h3>Strategy 5: Build Topical Authority, Not Domain Authority</h3>
<p>Perplexity trusts specialists over generalists. A website with 30 articles about email marketing will get cited for email marketing queries over a website with 1,000 articles about random topics.</p>
<p>Build depth in your niche:</p>
<ul>
<li>Create <a href="/blog/write-pillar-page/">pillar pages</a> for core topics</li>
<li>Surround each pillar with 8 to 15 supporting articles</li>
<li><a href="/blog/internal-linking-blog-posts/">Link them together</a> with descriptive anchor text</li>
<li>Cover the topic from every angle: beginner, advanced, tools, mistakes, data</li>
</ul>
<p>This cluster approach signals to Perplexity that your site has deep expertise. It also builds <a href="/blog/what-is-topical-authority/">topical authority</a> that transfers to Google rankings.</p>
