<h3>Strategy 6: Add Statistics and Cite Primary Sources</h3>
<p>Perplexity values pages that contain specific data points with cited sources. When your page says "email marketing delivers $42 ROI per $1 spent (DMA, 2025)," Perplexity can verify that claim and confidently cite your page as evidence.</p>
<p>Pages without data or with uncited claims are harder for Perplexity to trust. Add at least 3 to 5 statistics per article. Link each statistic to its primary source. This is the same pattern that strengthens <a href="/blog/eeat-google-quality-guide/">E-E-A-T signals</a> for Google.</p>
<h3>Strategy 7: Get Mentioned on Pages Perplexity Already Cites</h3>
<p>This is the "barnacle SEO" approach adapted for AI search. Find pages that Perplexity already cites for your target queries. Then get your brand mentioned on those pages.</p>
<p>How to do it:</p>
<ol>
<li>Search your target query on Perplexity</li>
<li>Note every source citation in the response</li>
<li>Identify which cited pages accept guest contributions, have resource sections, or cover related topics</li>
<li>Pitch to get your brand, product, or data mentioned on those pages</li>
</ol>
<p>When Perplexity scans a page it already trusts and finds your brand mentioned, it increases the chance your own site gets cited in future queries. This strategy works especially well for "[best X]" queries where list pages dominate.</p>
<h3>Strategy 8: Implement Schema Markup and Structured Data</h3>
<p><a href="/blog/schema-markup-for-blog-posts/">Schema markup</a> helps AI systems understand your content type, author credentials, and data structure. First Page Sage estimates schema contributes up to 10% of Perplexity's ranking factors.</p>
<p>Priority schema types for Perplexity SEO:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Article schema</strong> with <code>datePublished</code> and <code>dateModified</code></li>
<li><strong>FAQPage schema</strong> for question-answer content</li>
<li><strong>HowTo schema</strong> for step-by-step guides</li>
<li><strong>Organization schema</strong> with <code>sameAs</code> links to authoritative profiles</li>
<li><strong>Author schema</strong> with credentials and expertise signals</li>
</ul>
<p>Use our <a href="/tools/schema-markup-generator/">schema markup generator</a> to create JSON-LD for your pages. Test with Google's Rich Results Test to verify proper implementation.</p>
<h2>Technical Setup: PerplexityBot and Crawler Access</h2>
<p>Perplexity uses a web crawler called <strong>PerplexityBot</strong> to index and retrieve content. If your site blocks this crawler, Perplexity cannot cite your pages. Period.</p>
<h3>Check Your Robots.txt</h3>
<p>PerplexityBot respects <code>robots.txt</code> directives. Verify your file allows access:</p>
<pre><code>## Allow PerplexityBot
User-agent: PerplexityBot
Allow: /

## Also verify these AI crawlers are allowed
User-agent: GPTBot
Allow: /

User-agent: ClaudeBot
Allow: /
</code></pre>
<p>If your <code>robots.txt</code> has a blanket <code>Disallow: /</code> for unknown bots, PerplexityBot is blocked. Review our <a href="/blog/ai-crawlers-guide/">AI crawlers guide</a> for the full list of AI crawler user agents and recommended configurations.</p>
<h3>Verify PerplexityBot Access</h3>
<p>PerplexityBot identifies itself with this user agent string:</p>
<pre><code>Mozilla/5.0 AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko; compatible; PerplexityBot/1.0; +https://perplexity.ai/perplexitybot)
</code></pre>
<p>Check your server access logs for PerplexityBot requests. If you see zero entries, your WAF (Web Application Firewall), CDN, or security plugin may be blocking it.</p>
<p><strong>Common blockers:</strong>
- Cloudflare Bot Fight Mode (can block PerplexityBot)
- WordPress security plugins with aggressive bot filtering
- Rate limiting rules that block crawlers making rapid requests
- Geographic IP blocking that restricts Perplexity's server locations</p>
<h3>Speed and Rendering</h3>
<p>PerplexityBot crawls and reads your page in real time when generating an answer. Slow pages get lower priority. Pages that require JavaScript to render content may not be fully readable.</p>
<p>Optimization checklist:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Server response time under 500ms</li>
<li>[ ] No critical content behind JavaScript rendering</li>
<li>[ ] No content gated behind cookie consent overlays (PerplexityBot cannot click "accept")</li>
<li>[ ] No aggressive pop-ups or interstitials blocking content</li>
<li>[ ] Images have descriptive alt text (PerplexityBot reads alt text for context)</li>
</ul>
<h3>Set Up llms.txt</h3>
<p>The <a href="/blog/llms-txt-guide/">llms.txt standard</a> is an emerging protocol for telling AI systems about your site structure. Create a <code>/llms.txt</code> file at your domain root that lists your most important pages, their topics, and update frequency. Perplexity does not officially support llms.txt yet, but other AI systems do, and early adoption signals AI-friendliness.</p>
